Introduction:
For this project, we choose the article Mamba: Linear-Time Sequence Modeling with Selective State Spaces. In the paper, Mamba proposes a new sequence modeling architecture that replaces
Transformer attention with a “selective state space” mechanism. It keeps a running memory and decides what information is important to remember and what to ignore for each step, which 
helps the model focus on useful parts of the input without requiring looking at everything all the time. 

The two quantitative claims we want to verify in this paper are that “Mamba handles long context better than baselines,” because the paper argues that Mamba should do relatively better 
as sequence length gets longer. Another one is “Selection is necessary for strong performance.” The paper says the selective mechanism is the key reason Mamba works well, especially 
compared to older non-selective SSMs. 

